fields.title: Hot Potatoes & Bus Factors
fields.text:
Hot potatoes

These are the unsought tasks a team must routinely complete. The dirty dishes of a healthy organization. Team members often balk at the limited scope and impact of these duties and attempt to pass them off or delegate them down the chain of command. Though delegation of work is a necessary and strategic component of effective teams, leaders and members should make a conscious effort to distribute these hot potato tasks among more than just those in the lowest rung of the organization. For team longevity and burnout mitigation, thoughtfully approaching hot potato tasks is crucial.

Examples

  • Maintaining legacy code
  • Process documentation
  • Taking and distributing meeting notes
  • Tasks that fall outside the scope of the team's core responsibilities

Bus factors

In their book Debugging Teams, Brian Fitzpatrick and Ben Collins-Sussman provide a concise and relatable definition for "bus factor" on page six: "the number of people that need to get hit by a bus before your project is completely doomed.

 Or, in other words, resilient teams must ensure that clear documentation, sensible workflow, best practices, and competency overlap is achieved. Doing so helps to mitigate the potential disasterous effects if a key team member or members were to win the lottery, fall critically ill, resign unexpectedly, and suffer otherwise unforeseen catastrophies.

To add a whimsical element to this concept, image a team member just flying off like Mary Poppins propelled by an unserendipitous wind current—umbrella in hand.

fields.title: Everyday Dependencies
fields.text:
Unity and simplicity breed resiliency

Software dependencies are a topic worth serious consideration and discussion. Whether it be jQuery or a Python package, a dependency can greatly increase the complexity of an application. A common term for this among developers is "dependency hell". Dependencies also come with an inherent amount of risk and liability, as the dependency codebase must be actively maintained and audited for security threats. It is worth noting, however, that software dependencies offer the major benefit of being able to build from someone else's worth and not reinvent the wheel every time.

Everyday objects

It can be quite amusing to evaluate everyday objects for their depencies, and how they impact the object's overall utility. Relatable examples are a water bottle cap, a marker cap, and discposable batteries. Without these dependencies, a water bottle, a marker, and a wireless mouse are all either redered useless or severly impacted. Just as if a monkey in a chain of Barrel of Monkeys were to suddenly go missing or be compromised, the entire chain would suddenly halt its function and composition.

fields.title: Self-actualization
fields.text:
Chiseling oneself into greatness

The topic of self-actualization is one of my favorite things to talk about, think about, and act on. We build ourselves through every decision and person we associate with. Our self-expressive purchases, such as clothing, hairstyles, and events speak more to our ideals and aspirations for the future than they do to our current selves. A simple example I like to use is that of a relatable purchase, specifically a shirt or a bag. Our active choice in pursuing items and events that speak to who we eventually want to become is what determines what specifically we'll go with.

I fondly remember the winter of my freshman year of college. It was off-season, right between cross-country and indoor track. Our coaches encouraged us to write (with pencil!) down our goals and habits for this off-season period, to keep ourselves personally accountable. Well, I listed my daily routines and weekly mileage progressions to lay out the weeks ahead. Every run, accessory activity, and meal was a conscious effort on my part. I stayed the course, and my determination and discipline paid off immensely. I was in the best aerobic shape of my life, and made huge leaps in fitness and endurance.

Business use case

Self-actualization is a model to base other decisions around as well, since it provides a relatable framework for getting from point A to point B in a conscious and passionate manner. Dev teams can use self-actualization as a means to deliver top-notch products, by internalizing the mssions and goals of the endeavor.

fields.title: Be Shameless
fields.text:
Going for it

Take the risk, so long as it's informed and you're able to recover from any misstep. Many decisions are made out of hesitation and questionining of what the data are inferring, and therefore miss out on potential opportunities that reap significant reqards. Amazon's Bias for Action, one of their forteen Leadership Princliples, speaks to this point, adding on the observation that speed matters in business. I'd also say this is equally true for life in general. Approaching life based on informed decision making and bias for action, rather than simply saying "yes" to everything or constantly hesitating, has been an incredibly beneficial modus operandi for me over the past few years both personally and professionally.

fields.title: Contrasting SLU
fields.text:
Embracing duality

South Lake Union (SLU) leaves quite the impression. The stark contrast between workweek and weekend has made me reflect on how different contexts lead to different results. Having moved to the neighborhood in February 2018, I’m still energized by the contrasting productivity and tranquility the area offers.

Workweek bustle

Weekday activity is abound with flourishing activity, centered around the main Amazon campus residing at the heart of SLU. Upon moving to SLU, I was continually inspired by the productivity, work ethic, and determination of the surroundings. Admittedly, I was filled with lofty apsiration to one day best Amazon through running my own megacorporation. I've since now set back into realiy and appropriate goals, but the energy one is filled with by living here speaks volumes for the area and its communities.

Weekend meditiation

Just as the workweek is bustling with energy and movement, the weekend is void of expectations and embraces its own natural tranquility. The empty streets and lakeside setting amplify the introspective predisposition of the weekend. Quality of life is risen quite comfortably, though a walk along the lake, a relaxed grocery trip, or simple coffee and conversation with a friend. With much confidence, I can say that SLU is an extremely workable and liveable neighborhood.
